## 🧱 MODULAR ARCHITECTURE REQUIREMENTS

### File Structure

```

index.html           ← Minimal HTML shell: loads styles.css, single module entry script
styles.css           ← CRT effects, neon UI, HUD layout, scanlines, flicker
main.js              ← Entry point, instantiates Game
game.js              ← Main game loop (init(), update(dt), render(ctx))
raycaster.js         ← Raycasting engine: wall detection, sprite projection
player.js            ← Movement, collision, HP, infection debuffs
virus.js             ← AI pathfinding, targeting nodes, rule interactions
node.js              ← Node state management (infected/secured, effects)
rulesManager.js      ← Rule activation, timers, cooldowns, state flags
inputHandler.js      ← Keyboard/mouse input mapping
effects.js           ← Visual/audio distortion: shake, RGB noise, etc.
mapData.js           ← Hardcoded 64×64 map array (no external assets)

```

### Code Style Rules  
- ✅ Use ES6 classes and `export default class` / `import` in all modules  
- ✅ `camelCase` for variables/functions; `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for constants  
- ✅ All `.js` files use `"use strict"`
- ✅ Inline comments explain *why* (not what), especially around rule logic  
- ❌ No `console.log()` in normal gameplay—only major events (e.g., “Rule [3] activated”)  

### ES6 Module Entry Point
Do not generate sequential `<script>` tags. Use a single module entry point in `index.html`:  
```html
<script type="module" src="main.js"></script>

```

All dependencies will be handled internally via ES6 `import` statements at the top of their respective `.js` files.

